{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_012aKdtjnyB7NEWD8G2aKrNb","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.infrastructure.configuration;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.DeserializationFeature;\n     4→import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;\n     5→import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.SerializationFeature;\n     6→import com.fasterxml.jackson.datatype.jsr310.JavaTimeModule;\n     7→import com.github.slugify.Slugify;\n     8→import org.example.realworldapi.infrastructure.web.qualifiers.NoWrapRootValueObjectMapper;\n     9→import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;\n    10→import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;\n    11→import org.springframework.context.annotation.Primary;\n    12→\n    13→@Configuration\n    14→public class ApplicationConfiguration {\n    15→\n    16→  @Bean\n    17→  public Slugify slugify() {\n    18→    return Slugify.builder().build();\n    19→  }\n    20→\n    21→  @Bean(\"wrapRootValueObjectMapper\")\n    22→  public ObjectMapper wrapRootValueObjectMapper() {\n    23→    ObjectMapper objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();\n    24→    objectMapper.enable(SerializationFeature.WRAP_ROOT_VALUE);\n    25→    objectMapper.enable(DeserializationFeature.UNWRAP_ROOT_VALUE);\n    26→    objectMapper.registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());\n    27→    return objectMapper;\n    28→  }\n    29→\n    30→  @Bean(\"noWrapRootValueObjectMapper\")\n    31→  @NoWrapRootValueObjectMapper\n    32→  public ObjectMapper noWrapRootValueObjectMapper() {\n    33→    return new ObjectMapper().registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());\n    34→  }\n    35→\n    36→  @Bean\n    37→  @Primary\n    38→  public ObjectMapper primaryObjectMapper() {\n    39→    ObjectMapper objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();\n    40→    objectMapper.registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());\n    41→    return objectMapper;\n    42→  }\n    43→}\n    44→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e551caab-c624-46bd-b50e-a080c0cd7305","uuid":"0878ea9c-50fb-40cd-b8e9-8bc86036b2c0"}
